Setting
---
No story can survive on dialogue and action alone. The reader needs to have a world in their mind’s eye before the writer can start to fill that world with witty starship captains and enigmatic aliens.
- Break up long descriptions of setting by interweaving it with action. <%= link ">>>", "./pages/1578083491.leaf" %>

Exposition
---
A speculative story’s plot often springs from a novel idea: future technologies,
strange natural events, etc. The writer must make extra efforts to describe these
ideas clearly without boring the reader.

<%= notecard_plus 1583024581 %>

Sometimes, the best way to add a block of description to a scene is to interrupt the main narrative with a flashback (or flashforward). Flashbacks are a familiar device, and hiding the exposition within one is often more palatable to readers than an unclear interruption of indeterminable length.

- Use external analepses to build context around the main narrative. <%= link ">>>", "./pages/1582067416.leaf" %>
- Be inventive with the structure of flashbacks. <%= link ">>>", "./pages/1604374609.leaf" %>
- Flash forwards must have clear beginnings and ends. A smooth transition may take several sentences. <%= link ">>>", "./pages/1580270620.leaf" %>


